original_data.question:
A 16-year-old female presents to her primary care physician due to lack of menstruation. She has never had a period and is anxious that she is not “keeping up” with her friends. She states that her breasts began developing when she was 13, and she had a growth spurt around the same time. Review of systems reveals that she has also been getting headaches every few months over the last year with some photosensitivity and nausea each time. Ibuprofen relieves her symptoms. The patient is a competitive ice skater and has never been sexually active. Her mother has a history of migraine headaches, and her older sister has a history of bipolar disorder. Both underwent menarche at age 15. At this visit, the patient’s temperature is 98.6°F (37.0°C), pulse is 70/min, blood pressure is 118/65 mmHg, and respirations are 13/min. Her body mass index is 23.8 kg/m^2. Cardiopulmonary and abdominal exams are unremarkable. Both breasts are Tanner IV with no expressable discharge. Pelvic and axillary hair growth is also Tanner IV. The patient is unable to tolerate a full pelvic exam, but the part of the vaginal canal that is examined is unremarkable. Laboratory studies are ordered and are below:

Serum:
Na+: 139 mEq/L
K+: 4.1 mEq/L
Cl-: 100 mEq/L
HCO3-: 24 mEq/L
Urea nitrogen: 12 mg/dL
Glucose: 73 mg/dL
Creatinine: 0.9 mg/dL
Ca2+: 9.7 mg/dL
Mg2+: 1.7 mEq/L
AST: 11 U/L
ALT: 11 U/L
Follicle Stimulating Hormone (FSH): 16.2 mIU/mL (4.7-21.5 mIU/ml)
Estrogen: 240 pg/mL (64-357 pg/mL)

Abdominal ultrasound is performed and shows a normal uterus and ovaries. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?

model_response:
The patient’s history of delayed menarche, normal growth, and development of secondary sexual characteristics, along with the presence of headaches, photosensitivity, and nausea, are all consistent with a diagnosis of PCOS. The laboratory studies are also consistent with PCOS, as the LH:FSH ratio is elevated, estrogen levels are normal, and prolactin levels are within normal limits. The ultrasound is also consistent with PCOS, as the ovaries are enlarged with multiple cysts, but the uterus and vagina are normal. A normal uterus and ovaries rule out imperforate hymen and vaginal septum. The patient’s prolactin level is within normal limits, so hyperprolactinemia is unlikely.

Introduction:

Polycystic ovarian syndrome (PCOS) is a common endocrine disorder that affects 5%-10% of women of reproductive age. It is characterized by chronic anovulation and hyperandrogenemia. The diagnosis is made on the basis of clinical and laboratory findings, including menstrual irregularities, signs of hyperandrogenism, and polycystic ovaries on ultrasound.

Clinical features:

The most common presenting feature is menstrual irregularity, especially oligomenorrhea. The physical examination may be unremarkable, or it may reveal evidence of androgen excess, such as hirsutism, acne, or alopecia. Obesity is common, with the distribution of fat in the abdomen, as opposed to the hips (pear-shaped).

Laboratory findings:

Laboratory testing may show elevated levels of LH, low levels of FSH, and normal levels of estrogen and prolactin. Total and/or free testosterone levels may be elevated. Insulin levels may be elevated, especially in obese patients. Thyroid function testing should be performed because hypothyroidism may be present.

Imaging:

Transvaginal ultrasound may reveal the characteristic appearance of polycystic ovaries, with multiple cysts throughout the ovaries (neither cystic nor multicystic is preferred). The ovaries may be enlarged, but the size is not used to make the diagnosis.

Complications:

The most common complication of PCOS is infertility. Other complications include hirsutism, acne, alopecia, obesity, and impaired glucose tolerance.

Management:

The goals of management are to ensure normal feility, correct hyperandrogenism, and prevent endometrial cancer (caused by chronic anovulation and unopposed estrogen stimulation of the endometrium). Weight loss may improve hirsutism, acne, and glucose tolerance. Oral contraceptives can be used to suppress acne and hirsutism. Insulin sensitizers may be used in women with insulin resistance.

Medications used to treat infertility include clomiphene citrate, gonadotropins, and insulin sensitizers.

In women with chronic anovulation and infertility, progestin-containing contraceptives should be used to prevent endometrial cancer.


Conclusion:

The patient’s history, physical examination, laboratory studies, and ultrasound are all consistent with a diagnosis of PCOS.

Answer: OPTION D IS CORRECT.</s><s>

An article or book published after examination of published material on a subject. It may be comprehensive to various degrees and the time range of material scrutinized may be broad or narrow, but the reviews most often desired are reviews of the current literature. The textual material examined may be equally broad and can encompass, in medicine specifically, clinical material as well as experimental research or case reports. State-of-the-art reviews tend to address more current matters. A review of the literature must be differentiated from HISTORICAL ARTICLE on the same subject, but a review of historical literature is also within the scope of this publication type.

Isotope bone densitometers that use a single source to yield an essentially monoenergetic (one discrete line spectrum) beam of gamma rays (x-ray photons). In addition to the single photon source, these densitometers typically include a scanner, a single-channel analyzer, and a computer with appropriate software. Single-photon densitometers are used to assess bone mineral content in the appendicular skeleton, usually by measuring the forearm (radius) or the heel.

The action of specific antiporters in this class serve important functions such as allowing the efficient exchange of bicarbonate across red blood cell membranes as they passage through capillaries and the reabsorption of bicarbonate ions by the kidney.

Compounds that interact with ESTROGEN RECEPTORS in target tissues to bring about the effects similar to those of ESTRADIOL. Estrogens stimulate the female reproductive organs, and the development of secondary female SEX CHARACTERISTICS. Estrogenic chemicals include natural, synthetic, steroidal, or non-steroidal compounds.

The reproductive organ (GONADS) in female animals. In vertebrates, the ovary contains two functional parts: the OVARIAN FOLLICLE for the production of female germ cells (OOGENESIS); and the endocrine cells (GRANULOSA CELLS; THECA CELLS; and LUTEAL CELLS) for the production of ESTROGENS and PROGESTERONE.
